{
  "result": "On certain mornings the world feels like a library before opening: spines uncracked, dust settling in slow confetti, clocks whispering to themselves. I make coffee and listen to the kettle argue with the cold. Steam climbs the window and writes its soft, doomed letters, and for a few breaths I let them be my unread mail.\n\nThis is when small rituals earn their graduate degrees. The spoon remembers the mug\u2019s chipped rim. The plant on the sill turns a face toward weather no one ordered. A neighbor\u2019s bicycle rings twice, a tiny lighthouse, sweeping its little beam across the hallway of the day.\n\nSomewhere, news thrashes in its cage, algorithms shake their cups, and everything wants a password. But the table offers a grain that runs like a river through its history of dinners, and my thumb learns it by braille. The cat, who believes in gravity more than any physicist, drapes herself across the newspaper until headlines give up and purr.\n\nI have learned that attention is not a net but a lens; it does not catch the world, it brings it close enough to touch. So I practice noticing: the way the soap remembers rain, the pencil\u2019s patient thunder on paper, the distant train rehearsing its exit.\n\nBy noon, the library opens. Pages are borrowed, errands stamp their due dates. Yet the morning\u2019s hush lingers like a receipt in my pocket, proof that the day, however busy, began with permission to be quietly alive. I keep it anyway.",
